---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import RedSectionHeader from "../../components/common/RedSectionHeader.astro";
import HansSteinerCard from "../../components/consultant/HansSteinerCard.astro";
import BreadcrumbSchema from "../../components/BreadcrumbSchema.astro";
import ArticleSchema from "../../components/ArticleSchema.astro";
import FAQSchema from "../../components/FAQSchema.astro";
import QuickSummary from "../../components/content/QuickSummary.astro";
import ExpertInsight from "../../components/content/ExpertInsight.astro";
import RelatedArticles from "../../components/content/RelatedArticles.astro";

const metadata = {
    title: "Expat Guide to 3rd Pillar Withdrawal When Leaving Switzerland (2026)",
    description:
        "Your complete guide to withdrawing your 3rd and 2nd pillar assets when leaving Switzerland. Learn the rules for EU/EFTA vs. third countries and discover the 3a-to-3b conversion strategy.",
    canonical: "https://expat-savvy.ch/3rd-pillar/withdrawal-guide/",
};

const heroImage = "/images/leaving-switzerland-hero.png"; 

const faqs = [
    {
        question: "What is the withholding tax rate in my canton?",
        answer: "Rates vary significantly. While the average is around 7-10%, cantons like Schwyz or Uri are closer to 5%, whereas Geneva or Jura can be as high as 15-20%. This is why 'tax residence' during withdrawal is critical.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I reclaim the withholding tax?",
        answer: "Yes, if you live in a country with a Double Taxation Agreement (DTA) with Switzerland. You must prove you are paying tax in your new country and submit Form 7 to the relevant cantonal tax office.",
    },
    {
        question: "What's a vested benefits account (Freiz√ºgigkeitskonto)?",
        answer: "It is a specialized Swiss account where your 2nd pillar pension capital is held when you leave a job and don't immediately join a new pension fund. It keeps the funds in the 'pension system' while maintaining the tax-free status.",
    },
    {
        question: "How long does the withdrawal process take?",
        answer: "Typically 4 to 8 weeks from the moment you submit your official deregistration certificate and foreign address proof. Bank 3a is usually faster than insurance-based 3a.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I withdraw my 2nd pillar at the same time?",
        answer: "Yes, once you have deregistered. If moving to a non-EU/EFTA country, you can take 100%. If moving to EU/EFTA, you can usually only take the 'extra-mandatory' portion.",
    },
    {
        question: "What happens to my AHV when I leave?",
        answer: "Your AHV (1st pillar) remains in Switzerland. You will be eligible for a partial Swiss pension at age 65 based on the years you contributed. Non-EU/EFTA nationals moving to non-agreement countries can sometimes request a refund.",
    },
    {
        question: "Do I need to file a tax return in my new country?",
        answer: "Generally yes. Most countries require you to declare the arrival of large sums of capital. Whether it is taxed as income or considered a tax-free capital transfer depends on the specific laws of that country.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I leave my 3a in Switzerland after I move?",
        answer: "Yes. You are not forced to withdraw it. However, you can no longer contribute to it, and you must inform the provider of your new address. Some providers may charge a higher fee for non-resident accounts.",
    },
    {
        question: "What's the best strategy for withdrawing multiple pillars?",
        answer: "Stagger the withdrawals if possible. Withdrawing everything in one calendar year can push you into a higher progressive tax bracket. A multi-year withdrawal strategy is often more tax-efficient.",
    },
    {
        question: "Are there penalties for early withdrawal?",
        answer: "For 3a, there are no 'penalties' other than the withdrawal tax. For 2nd pillar, some foundations might have small administrative fees for the transfer to a vested benefits account.",
    },
    {
        question: "How does the 3a-to-3b conversion work?",
        answer: "This is exclusive to insurance-based 3a. Upon leaving, the contract is 'released' from the 3a tax rules and becomes a flexible 3b policy. You maintain your insurance cover and investment strategy globally.",
    },
    {
        question: "What if I return to Switzerland later?",
        answer: "You can open new 3a accounts and join a new 2nd pillar. Any funds you left in vested benefits accounts can be transferred into your new employer's pension fund to increase your retirement benefits.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I withdraw my 3a to pay off a mortgage before leaving?",
        answer: "Yes, this is valid even if the property is your primary residence in Switzerland. You can also withdraw 3a to buy property abroad as long as it will be your primary home.",
    },
    {
        question: "How is the withdrawal taxed in my new country?",
        answer: "Countries like Germany or the UK may tax the withdrawal as income, but usually allow you to credit the Swiss withholding tax paid. The USA generally treats it as a tax-deferred transfer if moved into a 401k/IRA equivalent (consult a CPA).",
    },
    {
        question: "What documents do I need for the withdrawal?",
        answer: "Official deregistration from the commune (Abmeldebest√§tigung), valid passport, proof of foreign address (utility bill), and your bank details for the payout.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I withdraw my 3a to start a business abroad?",
        answer: "You can withdraw it for becoming self-employed in Switzerland, but for starting a business abroad, the legal trigger used is usually 'leaving Switzerland' rather than 'starting a business'.",
    },
    {
        question: "What is the 'mandatory' vs 'extra-mandatory' portion?",
        answer: "The mandatory portion is the minimum required by law (LPP/BVG). The extra-mandatory is anything your employer contributed on top. This distinction only matters when moving to EU/EFTA countries.",
    },
    {
        question: "Can I move my 3a to a low-tax canton foundation?",
        answer: "Yes! Many savvy expats move their 3a to a foundation based in a low-tax canton (like Schwyz) shortly before leaving to lock in the lower withholding tax rate.",
    },
    {
        question: "Do I lose my insurance coverage when I deregister?",
        answer: "If you have a bank 3a with 'free' insurance perks, yes. If you have a dedicated insurance-based 3a, you can convert it to 3b and keep the coverage active worldwide.",
    },
    {
        question: "What if my destination country has no DTA with Switzerland?",
        answer: "The Swiss withholding tax becomes final and cannot be reclaimed. In this case, choosing a low-tax canton foundation (like Schwyz) is even more critical.",
    },
];
---

<Layout
    title={metadata.title}
    description={metadata.description}
    canonicalURLProp={metadata.canonical}
>
    <Fragment slot="head">
        <ArticleSchema
            title={metadata.title}
            description={metadata.description}
            image={heroImage}
            author={{
                "@type": "Person",
                name: "Hans Steiner",
                url: "https://expat-savvy.ch/about/hans-steiner/",
                affiliation: {
                    "@type": "Organization",
                    name: "Expat Savvy",
                },
            }}
        />
        <FAQSchema faqs={faqs} />
        <script type="application/ld+json">
            {JSON.stringify({
                "@context": "https://schema.org",
                "@type": "HowTo",
                "name": "How to Withdraw Your 3rd Pillar When Leaving Switzerland",
                "step": [
                    {
                        "@type": "HowToStep",
                        "text": "Determine your destination country (EU/EFTA vs. Non-EU)."
                    },
                    {
                        "@type": "HowToStep",
                        "text": "Check if you qualify for full withdrawal based on the LPP/BVG split."
                    },
                    {
                        "@type": "HowToStep",
                        "text": "Deregister from your Swiss commune and receive certificates."
                    },
                    {
                        "@type": "HowToStep",
                        "text": "Submit withdrawal request to your 3a foundation or 2nd pillar fund."
                    },
                    {
                        "@type": "HowToStep",
                        "text": "Receive funds and manage tax implications/reclaims."
                    }
                ]
            })}
        </script>
    </Fragment>

    <BreadcrumbSchema
        items={[
            { name: "Home", url: "/" },
            { name: "3rd Pillar", url: "/3rd-pillar" },
            {
                name: "Withdrawal Guide",
                url: "/3rd-pillar/withdrawal-guide",
            },
        ]}
    />
    <!-- HERO SECTION -->
    <div
        class="relative h-[75vh] min-h-[600px] flex items-center overflow-hidden"
    >
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/50 z-10"></div>
        <img
            src="/images/leaving-switzerland-hero.png"
            alt="Expat leaving Switzerland - Pension Withdrawal Guide"
            class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover"
        />

        <div class="container mx-auto px-6 relative z-20 text-center">
            <h1
                class="text-4xl md:text-7xl font-extrabold mb-8 drop-shadow-2xl leading-tight text-white mx-auto max-w-5xl"
            >
                Leaving Switzerland: <span class="text-[#C41E3A]"
                    >Your Pension Withdrawal Roadmap 2026</span
                >
            </h1>
            <p
                class="text-white/90 text-xl md:text-2xl font-medium drop-shadow-md max-w-3xl mx-auto leading-relaxed"
            >
                Withdrawing your pension is one of the most complex parts of
                leaving Switzerland. This guide provides a clear, step-by-step
                roadmap to ensure you maximize your assets and avoid costly
                mistakes.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA -->
    <main class="py-24 bg-white">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-6">
            <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
                <QuickSummary
                    summary="Leaving Switzerland requires a strategic approach to your 2nd and 3rd pillar assets. This guide covers the critical differences between EU/EFTA and non-EU moves, how to optimize withholding taxes, and the '3a-to-3b' conversion strategy for keeping your insurance coverage globally."
                    keyPoints={[
                        "Exit Strategy: The rules change drastically depending on if you move to an EU/EFTA country or a 'third country'.",
                        "Tax Traps: Withdrawing in a high-tax canton vs. a low-tax canton can cost you thousands in withholding tax.",
                        "Conversion Option: Insurance-based 3a policies can often be converted to 3b to keep coverage globally."
                    ]}
                />
                <!-- SECTION 1: THE 3A ADVANTAGE -->
                <section class="mb-32">
                    <RedSectionHeader
                        title="Pillar 3a: Your Key to a Flexible Departure"
                    />
                    <div class="spoke-body mt-8 space-y-6">
                        <p class="text-xl font-bold text-[#1a1a2e]">
                            Unlike the 2nd pillar, the 3rd pillar is remarkably
                            simple when it comes to international moves: <span
                                class="text-[#C41E3A]"
                                >it goes where you go.</span
                            >
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Pillar 3a assets can be withdrawn in full,
                            regardless of your destination country. Whether you
                            are moving to London, New York, or a remote island
                            in the Pacific, the Swiss government allows you to
                            close your 3a account and take the capital with you.
                        </p>
                        <div
                            class="bg-gray-50 p-8 rounded-[30px] border border-gray-100 my-10"
                        >
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-4">
                                The Standard Exit Process:
                            </h4>
                            <ul class="space-y-4">
                                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                                    <span
                                        class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-[#C41E3A] text-white flex items-center justify-center text-xs flex-shrink-0 mt-1"
                                        >1</span
                                    >
                                    <span
                                        ><strong>Deregistration:</strong> Visit your
                                        local commune and receive your official 'Abmeldebest√§tigung'
                                        (deregistration certificate).</span
                                    >
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                                    <span
                                        class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-[#C41E3A] text-white flex items-center justify-center text-xs flex-shrink-0 mt-1"
                                        >2</span
                                    >
                                    <span
                                        ><strong>Verification:</strong> Provide this
                                        certificate and a valid foreign address to
                                        your bank or insurance provider.</span
                                    >
                                </li>
                                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                                    <span
                                        class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-[#C41E3A] text-white flex items-center justify-center text-xs flex-shrink-0 mt-1"
                                        >3</span
                                    >
                                    <span
                                        ><strong>Payout:</strong> The funds are typically
                                        paid into a Swiss bank account in your name,
                                        which you can then transfer internationally.</span
                                    >
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            However, "can be withdrawn" doesn't always mean
                            "should be withdrawn." Before you cash out, you must
                            consider the <strong>withholding tax (Quellensteuer)</strong>. This tax is deducted automatically by the canton
                            where the foundation is based. While often
                            reclaimable under double taxation agreements, the
                            paperwork is tedious and mistakes can lead to
                            permanent losses.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- SECTION: WITHHOLDING TAX OPTIMIZATION -->
                <section class="mb-32 px-2">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-8 font-inter">Withholding Tax (Quellensteuer) Optimization</h2>
                    <div class="spoke-body space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            Withdrawal tax rates vary significantly by canton. While you might pay 15-20% in Geneva or Lausanne, the rate in Schwyz can be as low as 5%. This is a massive difference when withdrawing a life's worth of savings.
                        </p>
                        <div class="bg-red-50 p-8 rounded-[40px] border border-red-100 mb-8">
                            <p class="font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-2 uppercase tracking-tight">Tactical Advice:</p>
                            <p>
                                If you are planning to leave Switzerland, consider withdrawing your 3a while still residing in a low-tax canton (like Schwyz or Uri) before you deregister. <strong>This can save you thousands of CHF in withholding tax</strong> compared to withdrawing from a foundation based in Zurich or Geneva.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <ExpertInsight
                            insight="Most expats focus on the *logistics* of moving (movers, deregistration) and forget the *financial* logistics. The biggest mistake I see is cashing out the 2nd pillar when moving to the UK or USA without a tax strategy, often losing 15-30% to unnecessary taxes."
                            quote="It‚Äôs not just about getting your money out, it‚Äôs about keeping it."
                        />

                        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm mt-8">
                            <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
                                <thead class="bg-gray-50">
                                    <tr class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">
                                        <th class="p-4 border-b">Canton</th>
                                        <th class="p-4 border-b">Typical Tax Rate</th>
                                        <th class="p-4 border-b">Tax Profile</th>
                                    </tr>
                                </thead>
                                <tbody class="text-sm">
                                    <tr class="border-b">
                                        <td class="p-4 font-bold">Schwyz (SZ)</td>
                                        <td class="p-4">~4.8% - 5.5%</td>
                                        <td class="p-4 text-green-600 font-medium">Ultra Low</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr class="border-b">
                                        <td class="p-4 font-bold">Zug (ZG)</td>
                                        <td class="p-4">~5.5% - 6.5%</td>
                                        <td class="p-4 text-green-600 font-medium">Low</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr class="border-b">
                                        <td class="p-4 font-bold">Zurich (ZH)</td>
                                        <td class="p-4">~8.5% - 10.5%</td>
                                        <td class="p-4 text-orange-600 font-medium">Medium</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr class="border-b">
                                        <td class="p-4 font-bold">Bern (BE)</td>
                                        <td class="p-4">~12.0% - 14.5%</td>
                                        <td class="p-4 text-red-600 font-medium">High</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td class="p-4 font-bold">Geneva (GE)</td>
                                        <td class="p-4">~15.5% - 18.0%</td>
                                        <td class="p-4 text-red-700 font-medium">Very High</td>
                                    </tr>
                                </tbody>
                            </table>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- SECTION 2: THE 2ND PILLAR CRITICAL RULES -->
                <section class="mb-32">
                    <RedSectionHeader
                        title="The 2nd Pillar: Critical Rules You Must Know"
                    />
                    <div class="spoke-body mt-8 space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            The 2nd Pillar (LPP/BVG) is where most expats face
                            their biggest hurdle. Unlike the 3rd pillar, your
                            ability to access this cash depends almost entirely
                            on your passport and your next zip code.
                        </p>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 my-16">
                            <!-- EU/EFTA -->
                            <div
                                class="p-10 rounded-[40px] bg-blue-50/30 border-2 border-blue-100"
                            >
                                <h3
                                    class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-6"
                                >
                                    Moving to EU/EFTA
                                </h3>
                                <p class="text-sm mb-8 leading-relaxed">
                                    If you are moving to a country with
                                    mandatory social security agreements
                                    (EU/EFTA), your 2nd pillar is split.
                                </p>
                                <div class="space-y-4">
                                    <div
                                        class="p-4 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-blue-200"
                                    >
                                        <div
                                            class="text-[10px] uppercase font-black text-blue-500 mb-1"
                                        >
                                            Status: Restricted
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="font-bold">
                                            Mandatory Portion: LOCKED
                                        </div>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                                            Stays in a Swiss vested benefits
                                            account until retirement.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div
                                        class="p-4 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-green-200"
                                    >
                                        <div
                                            class="text-[10px] uppercase font-black text-green-600 mb-1"
                                        >
                                            Status: Available
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="font-bold">
                                            Extra-Mandatory: CASH OUT
                                        </div>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                                            You can withdraw everything above
                                            the legal minimum.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <!-- Third Country -->
                            <div
                                class="p-10 rounded-[40px] bg-red-50/30 border-2 border-red-100"
                            >
                                <h3
                                    class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-6"
                                >
                                    Moving to Non-EU/EFTA
                                </h3>
                                <p class="text-sm mb-8 leading-relaxed">
                                    If you are moving to a third country (e.g., USA, UK, UAE, Australia), the rules are simple.
                                </p>
                                <div class="space-y-4">
                                    <div
                                        class="p-4 bg-[#C41E3A] rounded-2xl text-white shadow-xl shadow-red-200"
                                    >
                                        <div
                                            class="text-[10px] uppercase font-black text-white/70 mb-1"
                                        >
                                            Status: Full Exit
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="font-bold text-xl">
                                            100% WITHDRAWAL
                                        </div>
                                        <p class="text-sm text-white/80">
                                            The entire balance can be paid out
                                            regardless of mandatory split.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-16">
                            <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-3xl">
                                <h5 class="font-bold text-sm mb-4">EU/EFTA Countries:</h5>
                                <ul class="text-xs space-y-2 grid grid-cols-2">
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Germany</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ France</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Italy</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Spain</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Austria</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Netherlands</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Belgium</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Portugal</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Norway</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Sweden</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-3xl">
                                <h5 class="font-bold text-sm mb-4">Non-EU/EFTA Examples:</h5>
                                <ul class="text-xs space-y-2 grid grid-cols-2">
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ USA</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Canada</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ UK (Post-Brexit)</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Australia</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Singapore</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ UAE</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Thailand</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Brazil</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ Japan</li>
                                    <li>‚Ä¢ South Africa</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <p>
                            <strong>Why this matters for your 3rd pillar:</strong> Because your 2nd pillar might be locked away for decades
                            if you move within Europe, your 3rd pillar becomes your
                            primary "liquid asset" to fund your move, buy a property
                            abroad, or start a business in your new home.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- SECTION: VESTED BENEFITS EXPLANATION -->
                <section class="mb-32 px-2">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-8 font-inter">Vested Benefits Account (Freiz√ºgigkeitskonto)</h2>
                    <div class="spoke-body space-y-6">
                        <p>
                            When you leave your job in Switzerland, your 2nd pillar assets are moved to a <strong>Vested Benefits Account</strong> (Freiz√ºgigkeitskonto). This is NOT your 3rd pillar; it is a holding tank for your employment-linked pension funds.
                        </p>
                        <div class="bg-blue-50 p-8 rounded-[40px] border border-blue-100">
                            <p class="font-bold text-[#1a1a2e] mb-4">The Golden Rule of Vesting:</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc ml-5 space-y-3">
                                <li>If you move to <strong>EU/EFTA</strong>, you cannot withdraw the mandatory portion of your 2nd pillar; it stays vested until retirement.</li>
                                <li>If you move to a <strong>Non-EU/EFTA country</strong>, you can withdraw the entire amount (mandatory + extra-mandatory).</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- SECTION 3: THE ADVANCED STRATEGY -->
                <section class="mb-32">
                    <div
                        class="bg-[#1a1a2e] rounded-[50px] p-12 md:p-16 text-white relative overflow-hidden group"
                    >
                        <div
                            class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-[#C41E3A]/20 to-transparent opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity duration-700"
                        >
                        </div>
                        <div class="relative z-10">
                            <RedSectionHeader
                                title="The Advanced Strategy: Don't Cash Out, Convert"
                                className="text-white"
                            />
                            <div
                                class="spoke-body mt-10 space-y-8 text-white/80"
                            >
                                <p class="text-white text-xl leading-relaxed">
                                    Most expats assume leaving Switzerland means
                                    they MUST close their 3rd pillar. This is a
                                    common and often expensive mistake.
                                </p>
                                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8 my-12">
                                    <div class="space-y-4">
                                        <div class="text-3xl">üîÑ</div>
                                        <h4 class="text-white font-bold">
                                            Continuity
                                        </h4>
                                        <p class="text-sm">
                                            Keep your long-term investment
                                            strategy running without
                                            interruption.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="space-y-4">
                                        <div class="text-3xl">üõ°Ô∏è</div>
                                        <h4 class="text-white font-bold">
                                            Protection
                                        </h4>
                                        <p class="text-sm">
                                            Retain valuable life and disability
                                            insurance‚Äîoften ungettable abroad.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="space-y-4">
                                        <div class="text-3xl">üí∞</div>
                                        <h4 class="text-white font-bold">
                                            Tax Efficiency
                                        </h4>
                                        <p class="text-sm">
                                            Final payouts can remain tax-free in
                                            Switzerland, even for non-residents.
                                        </p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">
                                    How 3a-to-3b Conversion Works
                                </h3>
                                <p>
                                    If you have an <strong
                                        >insurance-based 3a plan</strong
                                    >, you have the option to convert the policy
                                    into a flexible <strong>Pillar 3b</strong> plan.
                                    While you lose the tax deduction on future premiums
                                    (since you no longer pay Swiss income tax), you
                                    maintain the policy structure.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    This is the "Secret Weapon" for savvy
                                    expats: You secure your death and disability
                                    benefits globally and keep your equity
                                    investment compounding in a stable
                                    Swiss-denominated environment.
                                </p>

                                <div
                                    class="mt-12 p-8 border border-white/10 rounded-3xl bg-white/5"
                                >
                                    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
                                        <div
                                            class="w-12 h-12 bg-[#C41E3A] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-black"
                                        >
                                            !
                                        </div>
                                        <h4 class="text-xl font-bold">
                                            Bank vs. Insurance Reality Check
                                        </h4>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="text-sm">
                                        <strong>Important:</strong> You cannot do
